data.content:
In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. All four of your synchronous calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

The Cosmos DB SDK is inherently async-only. EF Core previously wrapped it with sync-over-async as a convenience, but that path is now gone — no configuration flag to re-enable it.

**Fixed repository:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.). `Add()` remains synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory; the actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
